@node "Installation" "Installation"
@next "Usage"
@prev "Dislaimer"

@{b}@{u}Installation@{uu}@{ub}

  1) With your Amiga turned off, plug the Palm cradle into an available
     serial port.  If your Amiga only has a 25-pin serial port then a 9-pin
     to 25-pin adapter will be required to plug the Palm's cradle into the
     Amiga's standard serial port.

  2) Use the Installer to copy the Spitfire files to your hard drive.  The
     installer uses the standard Amiga installer program and will install
     Spitfire and its appropriate files onto your hard drive.
  
  When Spitfire is executed for the fist time on a system, it will ask the user:
    1) to enter your user name id for the Palm*
    2) to set up the preferences and serial port settings that the cradle
       is connected to.
    3) to perform a HotSync of the Palm (therefore be sure to have your
       Palm ready and its cradle connected to your Amiga).

  This first time procedure will allow Spitfire to establish the proper accounts on your Palm and Amiga.
  If your Palm has already been HotSync with another computer, then Spitfire will recognize this and create a new account on your Amiga.  It will not overwrite a user name established on a Palm unless specifically told to do so.

  *(If you do not have a "virgin" Palm, then enter the same name that your Palm is synchronized with on the PC.  If a different name is supplied then Spitfire will create a new user profile).
@endnode

@node "Usage" "Usage"
@next "TipsAndTricks"
@prev "Installation"

@{b}@{u}Usage@{uu}@{ub}

  Please, also refer to the Palm's User manual for help with terms and operation.

@{b}@{u}Main Window@{uu}@{ub}

 The main graphical user interface window is divided into four main sections:
    1) User currently selected for HotSync in the top of the window
    2) Button bank located in the upper half of the window
    3) Log/Conduit Tabs (listviews) in the lower middle half
    4) Infomation window on the bottom of the window

 @{u}Image Tool Bar@{uu}
  Along the top area of the window there are several buttons:
    Install - Allows selection of applications to install at HotSync

    Datebook - Opens the Datebook application
    Address  - Opens the Address book application
    Memo     - Opens the Memo Pad application
    To Do    - Opens the To Do application

    HotSync - Begins HotSync according to Sync Opertions defined.
              To abort this process, double-click on the Abort button
              that appears in the requester.

    @{b}NOTE:@{ub} Datebook conduit is not completed currently


 @{u}Conduits@{uu}
  Here you can find a list of conduits that Spitfire supports.  In addition to the Date Book, Address Book, To Do List, and Memo Pad conduits, Spitfire includes a System and Install conduits.
  The System conduit backups up the system information stored in the Palm.  The Install conduit is used to install Palm applications.

  Double clicking on entries opens a window for altering conduit actions to be performed at HotSync time.  This allows customization for each conduit in setting the diretion in which you want to sync data.
  This customization can be saved for future use, or set for temporary use, which affects only the next hotsync, thus reverting back to their saved state.
  The supported sync actions are:
    1) Palm overwrites Amiga
       ·This will write information from the Palm to the Amiga.
       ·You can also refer to this as a backup.
    2) Amiga overwrites Palm
       ·This will write information from the Amiga to the Palm.
       ·You can also refer to this as a restore.
    3) Synchronize the files
       ·This will synchronize data between the Palm and the Amiga.
    4) Diabled
       ·This will turn off the conduit during a HotSync.

  The Install conduit has a different action when doubled-clicked.  Such an action open a window displaying the applications to be installed at hotsync.  This list can be altered by adding or deleting applications.

 @{u}HotSync Log@{uu}
  Displays feedback on the synchronizing opertations.


@{b}@{u}Settings Window@{uu}@{ub}

  The settings window is divided into two sections:
     1) Directories
     2) Serial Port

  @{u}Directories@{uu}
  Application Dir  - This is the default directory to where Palm
                     applications are normally kept on the Amiga.
  Palm Storage Dir - This is the directory where the pilot system and
                     conduits are to be stored on the Amiga.

  @{u}Serial Port@{uu}
  There are three parameters that require setting.
    1) Device - Select the serial device that the Palm cradle is attached to.
              - If your serial device is not present in the popup listview
                then please type it into the string gadget.
    2) Port   - The port on the serial device that the cradle is connected to.
    3) Baud   - The maximum speed that the serial port supports.

@EndNode

